  "prompt": "What is the oxidation number of nitrogen?",
  "response": "The oxidation number of nitrogen can vary depending on the compound it is in. Here are some common oxidation states of nitrogen:\n\n- In molecular nitrogen (N\u2082), nitrogen has an oxidation state of 0.\n- In ammonia (NH\u2083), nitrogen has an oxidation state of -3.\n- In nitrogen oxides like nitric oxide (NO), nitrogen has an oxidation state of +2; in nitrogen dioxide (NO\u2082), it has an oxidation state of +4; and in dinitrogen pentoxide (N\u2082O\u2085), it has an oxidation state of +5.\n- In ammonium (NH\u2084\u207a), nitrogen has an oxidation state of -3.\n- In nitrates (NO\u2083\u207b), nitrogen has an oxidation state of +5.\n\nThe oxidation number of nitrogen is thus context-dependent and can range from -3 to +5 in various compounds.",
